---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';

// Active-income treatment leads, because it is what makes oil & gas
// different from most other tax-advantaged investments.
const benefits = [
  {
    id: 'active',
    eyebrow: 'Benefit 1',
    title: 'Active-Income Treatment',
    tldr: 'Deductions offset W-2, business income, and short-term gains. Not just passive income.',
    detail: `
      <p>This is the feature that separates oil and gas from most other tax-advantaged alternatives.</p>
      <p>Under IRC &sect;469, losses from passive activities generally cannot offset wages or business income. That is the rule that blocks most real-estate paper losses from hitting W-2.</p>
      <p><strong>IRC &sect;469(c)(3)</strong> carves out a working-interest exception: a working interest in oil or gas is not a passive activity, provided your liability for the obligations of the activity is not limited. If the deal is structured correctly, deductions flow straight against ordinary income.</p>
      <p class="tip"><strong>How we preserve the exception.</strong> Investors in our funds enter as general partners during the drilling phase, which preserves the working-interest exception and year-one IDC treatment. After completion we convert to limited partners to cap ongoing liability.</p>
    `,
  },
  {
    id: 'idcs',
    eyebrow: 'Benefit 2',
    title: 'Intangible Drilling Costs (IDCs)',
    tldr: '65 to 85% of your investment is typically deductible in year one.',
    detail: `
      <p>Under <strong>IRC &sect;263(c)</strong>, operators and their investors can elect to expense (rather than capitalize) the intangible costs of drilling a well. In a typical onshore well, IDCs represent 65 to 85% of total cost.</p>
      <p>IDCs include labor, drilling fluids, site preparation, fuel, hauling, and bit repair. Anything that has no salvage value once the well is drilled.</p>
      <p class="tip"><strong>December close rule.</strong> IDCs paid or incurred by year-end for a well that begins drilling by March 31 of the following year are generally deductible in the earlier year (Treas. Reg. &sect;1.612-4). This is what drives the "December close, deduct this year" framing in energy partnerships.</p>
    `,
  },
  {
    id: 'tdcs',
    eyebrow: 'Benefit 3',
    title: 'Tangible Drilling Costs (TDCs)',
    tldr: 'The remaining 15 to 35% is depreciated, often with bonus depreciation in year one.',
    detail: `
      <p>Tangible equipment (casing, tubing, wellhead, pumping units, tank batteries, flow lines) is capitalized and recovered through depreciation on a seven-year MACRS schedule under IRC &sect;168.</p>
      <p>Bonus depreciation provisions have historically let investors write off a meaningful portion of TDCs in year one, though the bonus percentage has been phasing down under current law. Confirm the applicable rate with your CPA. It depends on when equipment is placed in service.</p>
    `,
  },
  {
    id: 'depletion',
    eyebrow: 'Benefit 4',
    title: 'Depletion Allowance',
    tldr: '15% of gross production revenue, deductible every year the well produces.',
    detail: `
      <p>Oil and gas are exhaustible resources. The tax code recognizes that with a depletion deduction against production revenue. There are two methods; eligible taxpayers generally take the higher of the two each year.</p>
      <p><strong>Percentage depletion (&sect;613A)</strong>. 15% of gross income from the property, available to independent producers and royalty owners. Not limited to basis; it can continue after you have fully recovered your original investment. Capped at 100% of net income from the property and 65% of taxable income overall.</p>
      <p><strong>Cost depletion (&sect;611 to &sect;613)</strong>. Allocates your adjusted basis across estimated reserves. Usually the smaller of the two.</p>
      <p class="tip"><strong>Enhanced recovery properties.</strong> Qualifying enhanced-recovery and marginal-production wells can carry a higher effective rate, sometimes into the 25 to 30% range. A number of our units fall in this category.</p>
      <p class="tip"><strong>Small producer cap.</strong> Percentage depletion is available so long as aggregate daily production does not exceed about 1,000 barrels of oil equivalent. Integrated majors are above the cap; virtually all private-placement investors are well below it.</p>
    `,
  },
];

const faqs = [
  {
    q: 'What about California?',
    a: `<p>California does not fully conform to the federal IDC rules. CA generally requires IDCs to be <strong>amortized over 60 months</strong> rather than expensed in year one. That does not eliminate the deduction; it stretches it out. For California residents, your federal and state K-1s will show different numbers.</p><p>Texas has no personal income tax. New York, Massachusetts, and most other states follow federal treatment on IDCs. Your CPA should be modeling the federal and state returns together.</p>`,
  },
  {
    q: 'What about AMT?',
    a: `<p>Historically, excess IDCs and percentage depletion were AMT preference items under IRC &sect;57 and could claw back part of the benefit. The Tax Cuts and Jobs Act raised AMT exemptions enough that AMT is rarely the controlling factor for individuals post-2018.</p><p>It still needs to be modeled case by case. For taxpayers with very large IDC deductions relative to regular taxable income, or with large SALT add-backs, AMT can still reduce the cash value of the first-year deduction.</p>`,
  },
  {
    q: 'Is there recapture at the end?',
    a: `<p>There can be. IDC deductions and depletion reduce your basis in the working interest, and on a sale, that basis reduction creates ordinary-income recapture under IRC &sect;1254 to the extent of prior deductions in excess of basis.</p><p><strong>In practice, we do not typically sell.</strong> Our model is to hold working interests and take distributions from ongoing production for the life of the well, not to flip the asset. If we never sell, there is no recapture event. If a particular deal does sell, the rate arbitrage (ordinary-rate deduction today against potentially capital-gain-rate treatment on the spread above basis) is still usually in the investor&rsquo;s favor.</p>`,
  },
  {
    q: 'How do you structure the partnership?',
    a: `<p>Every fund we run uses the same structure: <strong>general partnership converting to limited partnership</strong>. Investors enter as general partners during the drilling phase. That preserves the working-interest exception under &sect;469(c)(3) and the year-one IDC deduction. Once the wells are drilled and placed in production, the entity converts to a limited partnership to cap each investor&rsquo;s ongoing liability to their capital contribution.</p><p>This is the structure referenced throughout this page. The PPM and operating agreement describe the conversion mechanics in detail.</p>`,
  },
  {
    q: 'What should I ask my CPA?',
    a: `<p>Almost every question that matters here (AMT exposure, state conformity, timing of the IDC deduction, interaction with other passive losses, the right entity to hold the interest in) depends on facts only your CPA can see. The worst outcome is investing for the tax benefits and then discovering at filing time that your CPA does not understand K-1 reporting from a working-interest partnership.</p><p>We publish a free <a href="/resources">CPA interview questions guide</a> that includes a dedicated oil &amp; gas section. We are also happy to connect prospective investors with CPAs who regularly handle working-interest K-1s.</p>`,
  },
];
---

<Layout
  title="Oil & Gas Tax Benefits - Bidwell Capital"
  description="A plain-English guide to the tax treatment of oil and gas working interests: active-income deductions, IDCs, depletion, and the fine print."
>
  <section class="hero-sm">
    <div class="container narrow">
      <span class="section-label fade-up fade-up-1">Guide</span>
      <h1 class="fade-up fade-up-2">Tax benefits of oil &amp; gas working interests</h1>
      <p class="fade-up fade-up-3">One of the most tax-advantaged assets available to U.S. investors. Plain English up top, fine print where you can find it.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Stat bar -->
  <section class="section section-tight">
    <div class="container narrow">
      <div class="stat-grid fade-up">
        <div class="stat">
          <div class="stat-num">65&ndash;85%</div>
          <div class="stat-label">IDCs as a share of well cost</div>
        </div>
        <div class="stat">
          <div class="stat-num">100%</div>
          <div class="stat-label">IDCs deductible in year one</div>
        </div>
        <div class="stat">
          <div class="stat-num">15%</div>
          <div class="stat-label">Annual depletion on gross revenue</div>
        </div>
        <div class="stat">
          <div class="stat-num">&sect;469</div>
          <div class="stat-label">Losses offset W-2 &amp; business income</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- The hook: real example -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container narrow">
      <span class="section-label">From our last fund</span>
      <h2>$100,000 in, $99,000 deducted. Before a single barrel came out of the ground.</h2>
      <p class="lede">One investor in our most recent drilling fund committed $100,000 and was allocated approximately $99,000 in deductions against their 2025 ordinary income. This is the relevant line from their Schedule K-1:</p>

      <figure class="k1-figure">
        <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 640 220" role="img" aria-label="Schedule K-1 Partner's Capital Account Analysis showing $100,000 capital contributed, negative $98,671 current year net income, ending capital account of $1,329.">
          <rect x="0" y="0" width="640" height="220" fill="#ffffff" rx="4" />
          <rect x="2" y="2" width="636" height="216" fill="none" stroke="#1a1915" stroke-width="1.5" rx="3" />
          <text x="24" y="30" font-family="Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif" font-size="12" font-weight="700" fill="#1a1915">L</text>
          <text x="240" y="30" font-family="Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif" font-size="13" font-weight="700" fill="#1a1915">Partner's Capital Account Analysis</text>

          <g font-family="Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif" font-size="12" fill="#1a1915">
            <text x="24" y="58" font-weight="700">Beginning capital account</text>
            <text x="250" y="58" fill="#8a8479">. . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .</text>
            <text x="420" y="58">$</text>
            <line x1="440" y1="60" x2="620" y2="60" stroke="#1a1915" />

            <text x="24" y="86">Capital contributed during the year</text>
            <text x="250" y="86" fill="#8a8479">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</text>
            <text x="420" y="86">$</text>
            <text x="615" y="86" text-anchor="end" font-weight="700">100,000</text>
            <line x1="440" y1="88" x2="620" y2="88" stroke="#1a1915" />

            <text x="24" y="114">Current year net income (loss)</text>
            <text x="250" y="114" fill="#8a8479">. . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .</text>
            <text x="420" y="114">$</text>
            <text x="615" y="114" text-anchor="end" font-weight="700">-98,671</text>
            <line x1="440" y1="116" x2="620" y2="116" stroke="#1a1915" />

            <text x="24" y="142">Other increase (decrease) (attach explanation)</text>
            <text x="310" y="142" fill="#8a8479">. . . . . . .</text>
            <text x="420" y="142">$</text>
            <line x1="440" y1="144" x2="620" y2="144" stroke="#1a1915" />

            <text x="24" y="170">Withdrawals and distributions</text>
            <text x="250" y="170" fill="#8a8479">. . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .</text>
            <text x="420" y="170">$ (</text>
            <text x="620" y="170" text-anchor="end">)</text>
            <line x1="440" y1="172" x2="615" y2="172" stroke="#1a1915" />

            <text x="24" y="198" font-weight="700">Ending capital account</text>
            <text x="250" y="198" fill="#8a8479">. . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .</text>
            <text x="420" y="198">$</text>
            <text x="615" y="198" text-anchor="end" font-weight="700">1,329</text>
            <line x1="440" y1="200" x2="620" y2="200" stroke="#1a1915" />
          </g>
        </svg>
        <figcaption>Schedule K-1, Item L. Partner&rsquo;s Capital Account Analysis.</figcaption>
      </figure>

      <p class="pull-quote">For an investor in the top federal bracket, that is roughly <strong>$37,000 in direct tax savings</strong>. <em>Before a single barrel of oil came out of the ground.</em></p>

      <p>Unlike most tax-advantaged real estate, these deductions offset <strong>ordinary income</strong>: W-2 wages, business income, short-term gains. They do not sit on the sidelines waiting for passive income to absorb them.</p>

      <p class="kicker">The government wants domestic energy developed. The tax code is built to reward the capital that makes it happen.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- The four benefits, expandable -->
  <section class="section section-alt">
    <div class="container narrow">
      <span class="section-label">How it works</span>
      <h2>The four benefits, one level down</h2>
      <p class="section-intro">Skim the summary. Expand any card for the statute, thresholds, and gotchas.</p>

      <div class="benefit-list">
        {benefits.map((b) => (
          <details class="benefit-card" id={b.id}>
            <summary>
              <div class="benefit-head">
                <span class="benefit-eyebrow">{b.eyebrow}</span>
                <h3>{b.title}</h3>
                <p class="benefit-tldr">{b.tldr}</p>
              </div>
              <span class="benefit-chevron" aria-hidden="true">+</span>
            </summary>
            <div class="benefit-body" set:html={b.detail}></div>
          </details>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FAQ / fine print -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container narrow">
      <span class="section-label">Questions investors ask</span>
      <h2>The fine print</h2>
      <p class="section-intro">State conformity, AMT, exit treatment, deal structure. Expand what is relevant to you.</p>

      <div class="faq-list">
        {faqs.map((f) => (
          <details class="faq-item">
            <summary>{f.q}</summary>
            <div class="faq-body" set:html={f.a}></div>
          </details>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CTA -->
  <section class="section section-cta">
    <div class="container narrow">
      <div class="cta-box">
        <h2>Talk through a current deal</h2>
        <p>If you are evaluating oil and gas as part of a broader tax and cashflow strategy, we are happy to walk through our current offerings and how these mechanics apply in each one.</p>
        <div class="cta-actions">
          <a href="/contact#book" class="btn btn-primary">Schedule a call</a>
          <a href="/resources/oil-gas-tax-benefits.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="btn btn-outline">
            <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><path d="M21 15v4a2 2 0 0 1-2 2H5a2 2 0 0 1-2-2v-4"/><polyline points="7 10 12 15 17 10"/><line x1="12" y1="15" x2="12" y2="3"/></svg>
            Download PDF
          </a>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p class="disclaimer">Bidwell Capital is not a tax advisor, accountant, or law firm, and nothing on this page is tax, legal, or investment advice. Offerings are available only to verified accredited investors under SEC Regulation D. All investments carry risk, including the possible loss of principal. Past performance is not indicative of future results. Tax law changes frequently; rules summarized here reflect federal law as of the date this page was last updated.</p>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>

<style>
  .hero-sm { padding: 5rem 0 2rem; }
  .hero-sm h1 { margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem; }
  .hero-sm p { font-size: 1.125rem; max-width: 58ch; color: var(--text-secondary); }

  .section-tight { padding-top: 1rem; padding-bottom: 1rem; }
  .section-alt { background: var(--bg-secondary); }
  .section-cta { padding-top: 3rem; padding-bottom: 4rem; }

  /* Match the site-wide container width (1100px) used by /track-record and /about.
     Reading width is controlled per-element inside via max-width on text blocks. */
  .container.narrow {
    max-width: 1100px;
  }

  h2 {
    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
  }
  .section-intro {
    color: var(--text-secondary);
    margin-bottom: 2rem;
    max-width: 54ch;
  }

  /* Cap running text at a readable measure even though the container is full-width.
     Benefit cards and FAQ items fill the container intentionally. */
  .hero-sm p,
  .lede,
  .kicker,
  .pull-quote,
  .section > .container > p,
  .section > .container.narrow > p {
    max-width: 62ch;
  }

  /* Stat bar */
  .stat-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(4, 1fr);
    gap: 0;
    padding: 1.75rem 1rem;
    background: var(--bg-secondary);
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: var(--radius-lg);
  }
  .stat {
    padding: 0 1rem;
    border-right: 1px solid var(--border);
    text-align: center;
  }
  .stat:last-child { border-right: none; }
  .stat-num {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: clamp(1.5rem, 3vw, 2.125rem);
    color: var(--accent);
    line-height: 1.1;
    margin-bottom: 0.35rem;
  }
  .stat-label {
    font-size: 0.8125rem;
    color: var(--text-secondary);
    line-height: 1.4;
  }
  @media (max-width: 900px) {
    .stat-grid {
      grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr);
      gap: 1.25rem 0;
      padding: 1.5rem 0.5rem;
    }
    .stat { border-right: none; }
    .stat:nth-child(odd) { border-right: 1px solid var(--border); }
  }
  @media (max-width: 500px) {
    .stat-grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr; gap: 1.25rem; }
    .stat { border-right: none !important; }
  }

  /* Hook section */
  .lede {
    font-size: 1.0625rem;
    color: var(--text-secondary);
    margin: 1rem 0 1.5rem;
  }

  .k1-figure {
    margin: 1.5rem 0;
    padding: 1rem;
    background: var(--bg-secondary);
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: var(--radius);
    max-width: 46rem;
  }
  .k1-figure svg {
    width: 100%;
    height: auto;
    display: block;
    border-radius: var(--radius-sm);
  }
  .k1-figure figcaption {
    margin-top: 0.75rem;
    font-size: 0.8125rem;
    color: var(--text-tertiary);
    line-height: 1.5;
    text-align: center;
  }

  .pull-quote {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: 1.25rem;
    line-height: 1.5;
    color: var(--text-primary);
    border-left: 2px solid var(--accent);
    padding: 0.5rem 0 0.5rem 1.25rem;
    margin: 1.75rem 0;
  }
  .pull-quote strong { font-weight: 400; }
  .pull-quote em { font-style: italic; color: var(--text-secondary); }

  .kicker {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: 1.0625rem;
    line-height: 1.55;
    color: var(--accent);
    margin-top: 2rem;
  }

  /* Benefit cards */
  .benefit-list {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 0.75rem;
  }
  .benefit-card {
    background: var(--bg);
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: var(--radius);
    transition: border-color var(--transition);
  }
  .benefit-card:hover { border-color: var(--border-strong); }
  .benefit-card[open] { border-color: var(--accent); }

  .benefit-card > summary {
    list-style: none;
    cursor: pointer;
    padding: 1.25rem 1.5rem;
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr auto;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 1rem;
  }
  .benefit-card > summary::-webkit-details-marker { display: none; }

  .benefit-eyebrow {
    font-size: 0.75rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.1em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--accent);
    display: block;
    margin-bottom: 0.35rem;
  }
  .benefit-head h3 {
    font-size: 1.125rem;
    margin: 0;
    color: var(--text-primary);
  }
  .benefit-tldr {
    margin-top: 0.25rem;
    color: var(--text-secondary);
    font-size: 0.9375rem;
    line-height: 1.55;
  }
  .benefit-chevron {
    font-size: 1.5rem;
    color: var(--accent);
    line-height: 1;
    width: 1.25rem;
    text-align: center;
    transition: transform var(--transition);
  }
  .benefit-card[open] > summary > .benefit-chevron { transform: rotate(45deg); }

  .benefit-body {
    padding: 0 1.5rem 1.5rem;
    border-top: 1px dashed var(--border);
    padding-top: 1rem;
    margin-top: 0.25rem;
    color: var(--text-secondary);
  }
  .benefit-body p {
    margin-bottom: 0.85rem;
    line-height: 1.7;
  }
  .benefit-body p.tip {
    background: var(--accent-subtle);
    border-radius: var(--radius-sm);
    padding: 0.75rem 1rem;
    color: var(--text-primary);
    font-size: 0.9375rem;
    margin-top: 0.75rem;
  }
  .benefit-body strong { color: var(--text-primary); font-weight: 500; }

  /* FAQ */
  .faq-list {
    border-top: 1px solid var(--border);
  }
  .faq-item {
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);
  }
  .faq-item > summary {
    list-style: none;
    cursor: pointer;
    padding: 1.15rem 0;
    font-weight: 500;
    color: var(--text-primary);
    display: flex;
    justify-content: space-between;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 1rem;
  }
  .faq-item > summary::-webkit-details-marker { display: none; }
  .faq-item > summary::after {
    content: '+';
    color: var(--accent);
    font-size: 1.25rem;
    line-height: 1;
    flex-shrink: 0;
  }
  .faq-item[open] > summary::after { content: '\2212'; }
  .faq-body {
    padding: 0 0 1.25rem;
    color: var(--text-secondary);
  }
  .faq-body p {
    margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
    line-height: 1.7;
  }
  .faq-body ul {
    margin: 0 0 0.75rem 1.25rem;
  }
  .faq-body li {
    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
    line-height: 1.7;
  }
  .faq-body strong { color: var(--text-primary); font-weight: 500; }
  .faq-body a { color: var(--accent); }

  /* CTA */
  .cta-box {
    padding: 2.5rem 2rem;
    background: var(--bg-secondary);
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: var(--radius-lg);
    margin-bottom: 2rem;
    text-align: center;
  }
  .cta-box h2 {
    font-size: clamp(1.375rem, 2.5vw, 1.75rem);
    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
  }
  .cta-box p {
    color: var(--text-secondary);
    margin: 0 auto;
    max-width: 52ch;
  }
  .cta-actions {
    display: flex;
    gap: 0.75rem;
    justify-content: center;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    margin-top: 1.75rem;
  }
  .cta-actions .btn { white-space: nowrap; }

  .disclaimer {
    font-size: 0.8125rem;
    color: var(--text-tertiary);
    line-height: 1.65;
  }
</style>
